<div class="indented"><a id="comment-14861"></a>
  <div class="comment">
    <h3 class="title"><a href="/electric-cars-peak-grid-power-not-small-ones-perhaps-tesla#comment-14861" class="active">A huge difference, but</a></h3>    <div class="submitted">Submitted by <a href="/user/brad" title="View user profile." rel="nofollow">brad</a> on Sun, 2014-01-12 22:12.</div>
    <div class="content"><p>Serious deployment of electric cars would generate a lot of new electrical demand.  That a lot would happen at night is good for the grid, but there is still money to be spent.</p>

<p>Many people will also be keen to charge in the morning after they get to work.  You like to keep your battery between about 50% and 80% if you can.  The morning is not a peak time, but it&#8217;s not the night either.</p>

<p>Cars like the LEAF and other 80 mile range electrics essentially make you want to charge wherever and whenever you can.</p>
</div>
